Introduction

When you want to fit a model to your data, often you need it in certain forms. That form is usually called normal. In Statistics, you will often see the normality assumption, or homoskedasticity, or independence etc. In this lab we will cover the first one, transform our data to satisfy normality, which will also solve the homoskedasticity too.

Another topic that youâ€™ll cover this week is sampling. It is the magic behind the statistics, the source of knowledge and undeniable truth behind all, well at least some. Accordingly, if you collect data randomly and calculate itâ€™s average, the number you can get is yet another random variable, and it is always normal. It will be detailed below.

In this tutorial you will learn how to:

  • Transforming the data using a parametric transformation method
  • Checking whether central limit theorem holds for the house dataset with non-normal even non-continuous random variables.

Getting Started

  1. Load house_subset.csv data.
  2. some packages including
  • tidyverse
  • qqtest
library('tidyverse')
theme_set(theme_minimal())
houses <- read.csv('../Lab 3/house_subset.csv') # choose your directory!

Letâ€™s see our pain. The below wierd looking graph is unwelcomed in statistics. The reason is we want to explain a relationship but the data is not spreaded evenly:

library('ggExtra')
p <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=sqft_living, y=price)) + 
  geom_point(alpha=.1) + 
  geom_smooth(colour='firebrick')

ggMarginal(p, type = 'histogram')

Both variables are right skewed. When we draw the scatterplot, the data is grouped into certain intervals, and the rest is sprinkled all around. In other words, for the low values the data is condensed around the line (variance is low) but for the higher values the data is covering a wider range around the line (variance is high). This is known as heteroskedasticity and as you will see later when covering regressions, it is trouble.

We will show you how to obtain a normal looking dataset using transformations:

library(gridExtra)
g1 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=price)) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g2 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=sqrt(price))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g3 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=log(price))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

g4 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=sqft_living)) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g5 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=sqrt(sqft_living))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g6 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=log(sqft_living))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

grid.arrange(g1,g4,g2,g5,g3,g6)

price and sqft_living are originally right skewed. The sqrt transformation doesnâ€™t make it symmetric but the most symmetric one seems to be log-transformed one.

library('qqtest')
qqtest(log(houses$price))

qqtest(log(houses$sqft_living))

The log transformation for sqft_living worked fine. qqtest shows it is in the envelope, so we cannot reject it to be normal. But for price data we need more work. The edges are still out of the band.

Parametric Transformations

When you see dreams, things appear possible there. I, for example, have obtained an object which was dimensionless, like a point in my dream. When I woke up it I couldnâ€™t find it again.

Fortunately, there is a transformation found by statisticians in their conscious mind. Here is the formula:

\[T(x,\alpha) = \frac{x^\alpha-1}{\alpha}\]

The above formula is a general form of the transformations you can use. For example, when \(\alpha = 1\), the above will be equal to the original series. When \(\alpha = 0.5\), it will be \(2\sqrt{x}-2\), which is equivalent to \(\sqrt{x}\). When \(x\rightarrow 0\), the equation goes to \(\ln x\).

It can be defined in R as:

tform <- function(x, alpha){
  if(alpha == 0) {log(x)} else {(x^alpha-1)/alpha}
}
g1 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(price,1))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g2 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(price,0.5))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g3 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(price,0))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

g4 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(sqft_living,1))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g5 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(sqft_living,.5))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g6 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(sqft_living,0))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

grid.arrange(g1,g4,g2,g5,g3,g6)

The advantage of the above is to allow for further values. For example for data needs transformation between log and sqrt, we can use values between 0 to 0.5. Or for left-skewed data we can use negative values:

g1 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(price,0))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g2 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(price,-0.25))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g3 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(price,-.5))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

grid.arrange(g1,g2,g3)

We reached the sweet spot when alpha = -0.25.

Letâ€™s verify if it is normal enough:

qqtest(tform(houses$price,-0.25))

The line is not perfectly linear, but it is in the band. So it is hard to reject it is not normal.

After the transformation, the relation is easier to model:

p <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=log(sqft_living), y=tform(price,-.25))) + 
  geom_point(alpha=.1) + 
  geom_smooth(colour='firebrick')

ggMarginal(p, type = 'histogram')

The plot is now better, we can see the relation smoother than the previous case. The spreaded points are now gathered around the line

Sampling

In statistics, the central limit theorem suggests for any random variable \(X\):

\[Z \sim \frac{\bar X_i - \mu}{\sigma/\sqrt n}\]

In other words, if I take any data (assume that it is the population) whose average is \(\mu\) and standard deviation is \(\sigma\), take random samples from the data (\(X_i\)) and calculate averages (\(\bar X_i\)) then the distribution of \(\bar X_i\) must be standard normal. This must hold for any type of data.

Letâ€™s do it with sqft_living. The data is not normal at all:

ggplot(houses, aes(x=sqft_living)) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

The mean and standard deviation of the data is:

mu    <- mean(houses$sqft_living)
sigma <- sd(houses$sqft_living)

Now letâ€™s take random samples and calculate their averages. For \(n=300\), we can generate random samples as follows.

  • First, we will generate 7633 numbers each taking value from 1 to 25 with replacing,
  • then, we will give these numbers as groups of each observation (here house)
  • when assigned each house will be assigned randomly to group 1, 2, â€¦, 300
  • then we will take each groups averages. These will be \(X_i\) for \(i \in [1,300]\):
groups <- sample(1:300, size = nrow(houses), replace = T)
head(groups)
## [1] 187 164  46 176 197 103
houses$group <- groups
houses %>% select(date:sqft_living, group) %>% head
##              date   price bedrooms bathrooms sqft_living group
## 1 20141209T000000  538000        3      2.25        2570   187
## 2 20140512T000000 1225000        4      4.50        5420   164
## 3 20140627T000000  257500        3      2.25        1715    46
## 4 20150124T000000  650000        4      3.00        2950   176
## 5 20140731T000000  395000        3      2.00        1890   197
## 6 20150424T000000  230000        3      1.00        1250   103
Xbars <- houses %>% group_by(group) %>% summarize(Xbar=mean(sqft_living)) 
ggplot(Xbars, aes(x=(Xbar-mu)/(sigma/sqrt(300)))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

It looks normal.

But is it?

qqtest(Xbars$Xbar) 

# we could also write
# qqtest((Xbars$Xbar-mu)/(sigma/sqrt(300))) 
# but qqtest does not need it.

Magic!

Letâ€™s do the magic with the prices data:

set.seed(156)
groups <- sample(1:100, size = nrow(houses), replace = T)
houses$group <- groups

mu    <- mean(houses$price)
sigma <- sd(houses$price)

Xbars <- houses %>% group_by(group) %>% summarize(Xbar=mean(price)) 

ggplot(Xbars, aes(x=(Xbar-mu)/(sigma/sqrt(300)))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

qqtest(Xbars$Xbar)

Magic!

What about # bedrooms? It is discrete, but normal is continuous.

set.seed(36)
groups <- sample(1:300, size = nrow(houses), replace = T)
houses$group <- groups

mu    <- mean(houses$bedrooms)
sigma <- sd(houses$bedrooms)

Xbars <- houses %>% group_by(group) %>% summarize(Xbar=mean(bedrooms)) 

ggplot(Xbars, aes(x=(Xbar-mu)/(sigma/sqrt(300)))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

qqtest(Xbars$Xbar)

Magic!
